_ Nash said that she worked closely
with King through her involvement
with the Freedom Rides, even going
on a double—date with her husband
and King and his wife Coretta.

“Martin probably had mixed
feelings about me personally,” Nash
said. “He probably thought I was a
pain in the neck, but he acted re-
spectfully most of the time.”

Nash served as coordinator of

the Nashville Freedom Ride. Her
job included speaking to the press,
recruiting more Riders and gaining
national support for the Freedom
Riders’ cause. Freedom Rides were
trips across several states, usually
beginning in northern states and
ending in southern states. The Rides
protested segregation of interstate
transportation, such as Greyhound
buses.

“Our oﬂice was open 24/7,” Nash
said. “Pretty soon we had Freedom
Riders coming from all over the
country.”

In her speech, Nash connected
her involvement in the civil rights
movement to the steps necessary
for young people today to conduct
similar social change through non-
violence.

While a student at Fisk Univer-
sity in Nashville, Tenn., Nash took
classes in nonviolent direct action

